# How To Make Dashboards, Graphs, and Monitors in DataDog

## Making A New Dashboard

![][image1]  
Go to nav bar \> Dashboards \> New Dashboard. You can click the title area in the upper left of the dashboard to edit the name of it. When you’ve created a new dashboard, you’ll want to create an environment variable with a select box![][image2]. You do this by clicking “Edit” beneath the title of your dashboard, then click the “+” icon to add a new variable. For “Variable tag”, choose “env”, also give it a “Variable name” of “env”. Then, select the following values by clicking “Configure Dropdown Values”, and setting the “Default value” to “eks-prod”, and for the “Available values” select “eks-prod”, “eks-dev”, “eks-staging”, and “eks-sandbox”. This will create a variable that you can scope your graph and monitor queries to called *$env*.  
![][image3]

## Making new Graphs and Widgets

![][image4]  
Click “+ Add Widgets” in the upper right corner of the dashboard you created. This will open a nav bar on the right where you can select various widgets to drag into the dashboard area.  
![][image5]  
Drag and drop the type of graph you want to create into the main dashboard area. For example, let’s make a “Timeseries” graph. Once you drag it over, it will open it to the edit screen for the graph. 

![][image6]

### Setting Up a Query For Your Graph

#### Queries Using Logs

1. In the area called “Graph your data”, you’ll see a query interface for the first query by default labeled “a”.  
2. In the first select box, you can click it and select “Logs”.  
3. In the next select box, you can select “Indexes”.  
4. In the text input field called “Filter your logs”, you enter your query values.  
5. In the case of a log query, you would start by entering the title of your log in quotes, ex: “BenefitsDocuments::UploadStatusUpdater”. You would find this in your Rails logger code as the first parameter string you created for *::Rails.logger.info, ::Rails.logger.error*, etc.  
6. If you also want to filter by additional attributes that you logged, you can add *@payload.**NAME\_OF\_ATTRIBUTE**:**VALUE\_OF\_ATTRIBUTE\_YOU\_WANT\_TO\_FILTER\_BY*** , in this example it would be @payload.status:SUCCESS![][image7]  
7. Add the $env variable you created earlier to your query, so it will be scoped to whichever environment you select in the Env select box for the Dashboard.  
8. By default, the query is set to show count of all logs found, grouped by everything. This is fine for most simple graphs that are trying to show counts of logs coming in. Like number of errors.  
9. The “rollup” should probably be left on “auto” which will automatically chunk the graph points in increments that are useful for whatever timeframe your graph or dashboard is set to. This can be selected in the select box in the upper right of your dashboard.  
10. Beneath the query area, you can do things like select the color scheme for the graph display, and choose between “lines”, “bars”, or “areas”.  
11. At the very bottom of this UI, you can give your graph a name.  
12. Click “Save” when your done to see your new graph on the dashboard.

    

#### Queries Using Metrics

1. In the area called “Graph your data”, you’ll see a query interface for the first query by default labeled “a”.  
2. In the first select box, you can click it and select “Metrics”.  
3. In this example, the metric we’re using is a StatsD custom metric that we are logging from our Rails code: *vets\_api.statsd.cst\_lighthouse\_document\_uploads\_evidence\_submission\_record\_created* . One thing to note here is that custom StatsD metrics from Rails code start with vets\_api.statsd. And continue with the custom metric name but with the “.” converted to “\_”. So *vets\_api.statsd.cst.lighthouse.document.uploads.evidence.submission.record.created* would actually be *vets\_api.statsd.cst\_lighthouse\_document\_uploads\_evidence\_submission\_record\_created* in DataDog  
4. You’ll want to add the *$env* variable to the “from” field to make sure the query is scoped to the select environment.  
5. You’ll also want to “sum by” “(everything)” as “count”. This would change depending on what you want to do. So if you wanted to see averages instead of total counts, you could select “avg by” for example.![][image8]  
6. Beneath the query area, you can do things like select the color scheme for the graph display, and choose between “lines”, “bars”, or “areas”.  
7. At the very bottom of this UI, you can give your graph a name.  
8. Click “Save” when you're done to see your new graph on the dashboard.

### Making a New Monitor

![][image9]  
Go to Nav bar \> Monitors \> New Monitor \> Then choose a monitor type like Metric

The interface for this is very similar to the interface for a graph. The query works the same way.

#### “Set alert conditions” section

The primary difference is the “Set alert conditions” section. Here you can define the thresholds for when an alert is sent out.

#### “Configure notifications & automations” section

Alerts can be sent out via email and to Slack channels. In the textbox for this section, write an alert message and wrap it in {{\#is\_alert}} {{/is\_alert}} tags. This textbox uses markdown.

You also want to add a Slack channel reference. Click the “Slack” button at the bottom of the text box, and then “Add slack” and look for your channel. If you don’t see it, contact VA Platform and request a channel to be added. 

You’ll need to set “Teams”, “env”, “service”, and “itportfolio”. In the case of Benefits Management Tools, these would be:

- Teams: OCTO Benefits Portfolio  
- Env: eks-prod  
- Service: claim-status (or whichever app this alert is for)  
- Itportfolio: benefits-delivery

You may also want to add additional tags in the Tags textbox: team-group:management-tools and monitor:name-of-your-monitor. Adding the monitor tag makes it easier for you to reference from other widgets.

If you don’t know what value to put for any of these fields, you should ask VA Platform.
